
⸻

FG-101 — Clerk Pin Map (People • Desk • Phone • Email)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Map the humans who touch your papers; escalation needs names.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One sheet: Name • Role • Channel • Hours • Notes; add the main line + back line; log each contact with date/time.
	•	📝 Assignment: Build a 10-row clerk map for your court; add it to your case kit.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Intake—Ms. R (602-…); Supervisor—Mr. L (ext 212); Email: docket@…; notes: answers after 3 pm.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Systems move when people are reachable.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A small org card with phone and envelope icons.

⸻

FG-102 — The 3-Doc Starter Pack (Open Any Case Fast)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Begin with roadmap, timeline, order text—everything else stacks later.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Roadmap (Q/Std/Pins/Relief), Timeline (Date/Event/Pin/Effect), Draft Order (primary + limited-remand block).
	•	📝 Assignment: Create a 3-doc pack template you can clone in 2 minutes.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Q: Must court reach harm? Std: abuse. Pins: Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2. Relief: remand 21d (a–d).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Start small, signable, reusable.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: Three tiles clipped together: R • T • O.

⸻

FG-103 — Reply Discipline (≤2 Issues • One Screen)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Reply = answer what changed; nothing more.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Mirror headings; each point = SoR line + one pin + relief; cut everything not needed for the order.
	•	📝 Assignment: Reduce your reply to ≤2 issues and ≤70 words per issue.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse: wrong test (cite); harm not reached (Dkt 18:2). Remand 21d for findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Replies close deals, not debates.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A narrow column with two tight blocks.

⸻

FG-104 — OA Reserve Plan (Save :60 on Purpose)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Reserve a clean minute; script two pins + remedy.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Ask to reserve; track clock; if interrupted, pivot back to the close: standard → two pins → order line.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write your :60 reserve verbatim.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Abuse; harm not reached (Dkt 18:2; Tab 3 p.2). Relief: remand 21d for findings.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: The last thing said is the first thing signed.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A stopwatch with a highlighted final slice.

⸻

FG-105 — Page Budget (Words Follow Pages, Not Vice Versa)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Budget pages first: one for facts, two for law, one for relief.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Cap facts to pins; law to SoR + split map; keep a full page for the order and prejudice.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write a 4-line page budget for your opening brief.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Facts 1p (pins), Law 2p (SoR/split), Relief+Prejudice 1p.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Empty space is strategy, not waste.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A four-block layout with the last block labeled “ORDER.”

⸻

FG-106 — One-Pager After Loss (Plan • Pin • Ask)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Respond to bad orders with a single page: what changed, where to verify, what to sign.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Sections: Order line quoted • Pin that misread • Narrow remedy (clarify/72h stay/limited remand).
	•	📝 Assignment: Draft your after-loss one-pager template.
	•	✅ Model Response: “P.12 n.3 misstates harm; record Dkt 18:2; clarify or stay ¶3 for 72h; remand 21d if needed.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Short + surgical keeps credibility.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A one-page sheet with a highlight over one sentence.

⸻

FG-107 — Preservation Footers (Live Objection in One Line)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Add a footer line preserving error whenever silence risks waiver.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: “Plaintiff preserves objection to X (pin); relief sought Y.” Use sparingly; consistent voice.
	•	📝 Assignment: Identify 3 spots to insert preservation footers in your draft.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Preserves objection to omission of harm findings (Dkt 18:2).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Small lines save whole appeals.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A page footer ribbon that says “Preserved.”

⸻

FG-108 — Minimal Facts, Maximal Pins
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Facts persuade only when stapled to pages.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: For each factual sentence, show one Dkt/Ex/Tr pin; prefer images/tables over prose; keep adjectives out.
	•	📝 Assignment: Convert five fact lines to fact + pin pairs.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Mail delivered 07/31 09:42 (Ex A:1).”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: A pinned fact is a legal fact.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A sentence with a pushpin icon at the end.

⸻

FG-109 — Posture First Paragraph (Statute • Clock • Copies)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: Open with the triangle so no one hunts.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: One paragraph: §1291/§1292 (or analog), Rule 58 + FRAP 4 math, judgment/order tabs.
	•	📝 Assignment: Write your posture paragraph in ≤5 lines.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Jurisdiction under §1291; Rule 58 on 08/15; NOA 08/19; judgment/PI order at Tabs 1–2.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Comfort invites relief.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A triangle icon next to a short paragraph.

⸻

FG-110 — The Pin Sprint (Ten Minutes, Ten Fixes)
	•	⚖️ Core Message: A 10-minute pin pass improves a brief more than hours of prose.
	•	📖 Lesson Content: Timer on: scan headings; add one anchor pin per paragraph; fix two quotes; paste the relief bank; stop.
	•	📝 Assignment: Run a pin sprint and list your 10 changes.
	•	✅ Model Response: “Added 6 anchors, fixed 2 quotes, pasted order, trimmed adjectives.”
	•	💡 Reflection Summary: Momentum beats perfection.
	•	🎨 Visual Concept: A sprint lane with tiny pin flags at each mark